The paper proposes a framework for comparing multiple groups of documents, which involves representing the document groups and comparison criteria as nodes in a bipartite graph model. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category, which deals with techniques for searching and retrieving relevant information from large collections of documents. Additionally, the paper may also be relevant to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category, which deals with natural language processing and text analysis, as well as the Digital Libraries (cs.DL) sub-category, which deals with the organization and management of digital collections of documents. The paper's focus on graph-based algorithms and data analysis may also make it relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category, as well as the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category, which deal with the storage and retrieval of structured data.
